      "title": "[The Marginalian] Trauma, Transformation, and the Courage of Uncertainty: Prentis Hemphill on the Key to Breaking Our Patterns",
      "content_html": "<img src=\"https://www.themarginalian.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/herons_TheMarginalian.jpg?fit=1200%2C630&ssl=1\" style=\"width:100%;max-height:300px;object-fit:cover;\" />\n“There is no description of a life without an account of the changes that are possible within it,” Adam Philips writes in his superb meditation on our ambivalent desire for change &#8212; ambivalence brilliantly rendered in the Vampire Problem thought experiment, illustrating the paradoxical psychology of why have such a hard time changing, breaking the patterned ways of being by which we hedge against the fear of not knowing who we are, what we want, and how to be safe. Our paradox is that we are the pattern-seeking animal &#8212; a kind of superpower conferred upon us by our complex&#8230;&#160;<a class=\"h3 read_on\" href=\"https://www.themarginalian.org/2026/03/10/prentis-hemphill-trauma-change/\">read&#160;article</a>",
